	shorttitle = {White bears and other unwanted thoughts},
	abstract = {The research and ideas presented in these pages explore how people deal with unwanted thoughts, and what the pitfalls can be when their efforts take particular forms. . . . Although there will be no step-by-step lessons and no quick solutions, there will be information on what can go right and what can go wrong when we try to control our minds.  The following chapters explore the use of mental control in the struggle against unwanted thoughts. . . . Learning something about why and when we exercise mental control is one way to gain a sense of what it is, so we will examine the wellsprings of suppression in Chapter 2. . . . Chapter 3 examines the mental mechanics underlying the act of thought suppression. It looks at how the mind is constructed, and how the special format of this mental apparatus may constrain our abilities to suppress.  What people really do to suppress a thought is to think of something else, and this chapter [Chapter 4] is about the operation of the process of self-distraction. In Chapter 5, we examine how people engage in external processes of self-distraction—by changing their surroundings.  The next section of the book examines psychological processes that are influenced by thought suppression. . . . Chapter 6 inquires whether it is possible to change our beliefs and attitudes by the willful control of thinking, and as we shall see, there are often cases in which such change is hard to manage. Chapter 7 addresses another potential consequence of thought suppression—our ability to change our moods by changing our minds. . . . The related problem we explore in Chapter 8 is how mental control impinges on unwanted emotions such as anxiety and agitation.  The last chapter of the book takes up a theme that resurfaces at many points—the idea that suppression can create obsessions. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
