	doi = {10.1016/j.jad.2018.05.072},
	abstract = {Background
Parent–child interactions set the stage for child mental health and development. Given that maternal depressive symptoms are associated with poorer observed caregiving behaviors, examining the potential cognitive mediators is important in identifying mechanisms underlying the intergenerational transmission of risk and possible targets for intervention.
