	abstract = {A growing body of research suggests that language cues for deception are not universal. When settings change, the effect of deception on word patterns also changes, making it difficult to draw conclusions about the overall impact of deception on language use. In this chapter, we first outline why a universal approach to deception and language is problematic. Next, we consider how research has revealed the importance of various moderators (e.g., the mode of message production, the valence of the situation) on how language is affected by deception, suggesting that deception is a context-contingent phenomenon. We also address how language, independent of deception, is also highly context dependent. Finally, we outline the Contextual Organization of Language and Deception (COLD) framework, which proposes that psychological dynamics (e.g., emotional and cognitive processes modified by deception), pragmatic goals (e.g., what the speaker is trying to accomplish with his or her deception), and genre conventions (e.g., the norms of each discourse community that shape how language is produced) profoundly but systematically influence the effect of deception on language. We apply the COLD framework to a database of deceptive political speeches from six US Presidents (George W. Bush, Lyndon B. Johnson, Bill Clinton, Richard Nixon, John F. Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan), finding support for the idea that false language patterns are reliably modified by the deception type.},
	language = {en},
