	shorttitle = {Self-help therapy},
	abstract = {Recent developments in professionally developed self-help programs are best appreciated within a historical context. In its earliest form, "self-help" referred to the coming together of peers who would assist each other independently of professional assistance. Given the enormous popularity of self-help materials and their goal of helping people help themselves, it is not surprising that psychologists and other health care professionals have provided their share of advice. In the 1970s, there was an explosive growth of do-it-yourself books. Book publications continued in the 1980s, now accompanied by self-help audiocassettes and videotape programs. The self-help industry has expanded its reach in other ways. For example, in the area of parenting skills, there used to be general books of advice by authors such as Benjamin Spock. By the 1980s, there were individualized audiotapes that parents could play to children before bedtime for the more specific purposes of eliminating fears and bed-wetting, or improving self-esteem. This trend toward greater specificity of focus, coupled with multiple modalities for delivering instructional programs, helps to explain how the self-help movement has become such big business. More than four decades later, we continue to support the idealism of the 1970s, and we continue to believe that psychologists will play an important role in the development of effective self-help materials. Imagine, if you will, a multidisciplinary group of professionals who develop self-help programs, educate consumers in their proper use, and continually evaluate and improve these programs in the context of long-term public health projects. The future of an empirically sound self-help movement lies in this vision of "program-based" methods rather than "individually authored" products. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)},
